{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_iris_ver01/data/sn78002169/0027955890A/1946050501/0054.xml":{"full_text":"INCREASED LABOR\nROWS ANTICIPATED\nStrife Is Expected To Cen\nter Around Automobile\nParts Makers\nBy ROY J. FORREST\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nDETROIT, May 4\u2014fU.R) Inc\nin a labor troubles were predicted\ntodav by a spokesman for the au\nS3* industry, with. toNJ-JJ\nagement strife centering around\nthe parts makers. _ j\nMost of the major companies, j\nsuch as Ford. Chrysler. General\nMotors, Packard. Hudson. Studeba\nker and Nash, have signed con\ntacts with the CIO United Auto\nWorkers, but the UAW\u2019s wage drive\nis just getting started in the smal\nler plants.\nFrank Rising of the Automotive\nand Aviation Parts manufacturers, j\nInc representing 410 parts makers\nemploying 500.000 workers, said la\nbor uncertainties made planning al- j\nmost impossible.\n\u2022\u2018Judging from the attitude of la-\nbor in many of the parts plants, j\nwe are facing a worse period of\nlabor troubles than we have had i\nthus far,\u201d Rising said.\nStrikes among the parts makers\nand materia' suppliers have been i\none of the principal causes of limp-\ning automobile production during j\nthe reconversion period. Most dis\nputes have been settled on payment j\nof 18-cent hourly wage increases.\n\u2022'Local UAW officials are stiffen- j\n\u2022'Local UAW officials are stiffen- I\ning thei- attitude toward manage- j\ninert.\u201d Rising said. \u2018\u2018The UAW is\nmaking a concerted drive to elim\ninate incentive pays systems and\nis adopting an 'or else\u201d attitude.\u201d\nHe said that labor contracts I\namong the parte makers have no j\nuniform expiration date.\nFOR\nCORRECT TIME\nCALL 2-1575\n\u2014FOR\u2014\nCorrect Jewelry\nVISIT\nThe JEWEL BOX\nWilmington\u2019s Most Popular\nJewelry Store\n109 N. Front St.\nI\nFor\nCORONER\nVote For\nGORDAN\nDORAN\nlu. S. Army Evacuating\nj Exploding Bomb Dump\nContinued from Page One\nj farv tribunal courthouse some\n\u2019eight and one-half miles from the\nscene, all windows have been open\ned except those where Herman\nGoering and the other war crimes\ndefendants may watch are im\nprisoned. The plexiglass covering\ntheir windows bulges from the\nconcussion of bursting shells and\nrockets.\nIt was bright as daylight for\nmiles around the fire. Multi-color\ned flares lighted the area. The\nbrilliant, phosphorescent light dim\nmed to a reddish-brown glare when\nthe V-2\u2019s exploded.\nLieut. Tracy Madison of Tusca\nloosa, Ala., was one of the many\nwho were slightly injured by fat\ning shrapnel and debris. Althou,,\nhit in the chest by a flying rock,\nhe remained on duty.\n'\u2022The fire started around 5 p.\nm., after we put out three other\nsmaller ires during the day.\nwas notified at 5:30 p- m. and took\na bulldozer to make a fire-break;\naround the V-2\u2019s. Then I made a j\nfire-break around the flares, Madi- j\nson said.\n\u2022\u2022The first big blast came at;\n6:30, when a 42-centimeter con-]\ncrete piercing shell went off. j\nThere was another big blast at j\n7 o'clock, when a bunch of rocket\nflares went up.\"\nMadison said 29.000 tons of ex\nplosives were stored in the dump.\nBy 11 p. m., he estimated that 10,\n000 to 18.000 tons had blown up.\nCivilians Evacuated\nWithin four hours after the ex\nplosions began, 2.500 civilians\nabout 45 per cent of Feucht\u2019s\npopulation\u2014had been removed to\nHershbruck, 18 miles away, where\nthey sat on street corners and,\nwatched the glare from the ex- j\nplosions.\nThe smoke clouds hung over a;\nmile and a half area around the j\ncenter of the fire and explosions, i\nand the flames are spreading to\nward \u201cthe heavy stuff.\" Windows\nrattled, doors shook and plaster\nfell in Neurnberg, eight miles\naway.\nThe area in the immediate cen\nter of the Muna works which\nserved the Germans both as an\nassembly point and a dump is\nnot heavily populated. Neverthe\nless. the American Army was\nhelping evacuate Feucht\u2019s pe?ple\nin GI trucks.\nSchedule Announced\nFor Radio Programs\nSponsored By Church\nA series of six transcribed radio\nprograms will be broadcast over\nstation WMFD, beginning tomorrow\nand continuing through Saturday,\nin keeping with the local observ\nance of \"Christian Home Week.\u201d\nThe 15-minute programs are be\ning sponsored by the radio com\nmittee of the Southern Baptist\nconvention, in cooperati m with\neignt local radio stations through\nout North Carolina.\nSpeaker for the series is Dr. Wal\nter P. Binns, president of William\nJewell college, Liberty, Mo. Dr.\nBinns will be heard at 4 p.m., Mon\nday; 3:45 p.m., Tuesday; 4 p.m.;\nWednesday; 3:45 p.m., Thursday;\n3:45 p.m., Friday; and 2:30 p.m.,\nSaturday\nDry Dock Facility\nOffered For Sale\nContinued from Page One\ngarage and machine shop, and\nother minor buildings.\nThe property also includes a\nplant-owned sewage disposal sys\ntem.\nCredit terms may be arranged\nfor the purchase of the plant.\nAdditional information may be\nobtained from the WSA, 317 S.\nTryon street, Charlotte,\nSamuel Johnson published the\nfirst English dictionary in 1755.\n1 NOW AVAILABLE!\nThe NEW 1946 NASON\n6-Tube Superheterodyne Radio\nA 6-Tube Set At\nThe 5-Tube Price Of\n$2735\nHandsome Walnut Cabinet\nBuilt-In Aerial\nAutomatic Volume Control\nFactory Guaranteed\nMAIL ORDERS ACCEPTED!\nHOWARD RADIO COMPANY\n1027 South 3rd Street Dial 2-8095\nSENATORS URGE\nMINE SEIZURE\nBY PRESIDENT\nContinued from Page One\nto God for guidance to find a solu\nI tion to their problems.\u201d\n3_solid fuels Administrator J.\ni A. Krug said further curtailments\nI on soft coal consumption were nec\nessary to prevent the European re\nlief and rehabilitation program\nfrom collapsing.\nDemand Seizure\n4\u2014Sen. Scott W. Lucas, D., 111.,\ndemanded Presidential seizure of\nthe mines to stop what he said\n\"could easily become an insurrec\ntion against the government.\u201d Sen.\nC. Wayland Brookson r., 111., join\ned Lucas in demanding govern\nment action. UMW President John\nL. Lewis was denounced as a\n\u2022\u2018bully\u201d by Sen. Allen K. Ellender.\nD. La.\n5\u2014 Lewis was reported ready to\ndiscuss a settlement of the strike,\nonly if other issues including safe\nty and welfare provisions and pay\nment of $4,000,000 in claimed over\ntime wages are settled before\nwages and hours are discussed.\n6\u2014 Edward R. Burke, president of\nthe Southern Coal Producers assoc\niation, said in a radio speech\n(MBS) that the operators will agree\nto pay the best wages ever earned\nin the coal industry; negotiate a\nshorter work day and week;\n\u201cmove heaven and earth\u201d to pre\nvent avoidable mine accidents, ex\namine the extent of hardship cases\nand jointly establish a fund for\ntheir alleviation.\n7\u2014 The Army announced that, In\nkeeping with ODT restrictions on\nrailroad transportation, it will\nmove only troops returning from\nor en route overseas, and patients.\nMovements of all other groups and\nindividuals will be suspended in\ndefinitely. It said this will slow the\nmovement and demobilization of\ntroops in the United States.\n8\u2014 Sen. Harry F. Byrd, D., Va.,\nrevealed he has urged President\nTruman to give Lewis and the op\nerators three days to come to\nterms. Failing that, he said, Mr.\nTruman should exercise his pow\ners \u201cto prevent the catastrophe of\na shutdown of nearly all activities\nin America the country looks\nto the President for effective and j\nforceful action.\u201d\nrso Plan\nPresident Truman hinted Thurs\nday that he may order seizure of\nthe struck pits if the situation gees\nmuch graver. But informed sources\nhave indicated that the President\nso far has not developed a plan for\ntaking over the mines. The govern\nment apparently was doubtful that\nI the miners would return to work i\neven under federal seizure.\nMr. Truman's alarming view of1\nthe situation was spelled out in a\nreport prepared at his request by\nthe Office of War Mobilization and\nReconversion and issued through\nthe White House.\nWhite House Press Secretary\nCharles G. Ross said that Mr. Tru\nman ordered the survey because\n\"the President desired the public\nto be fully informed\u201d about the im\npact of the strike on reconversion.\nThere was speculation, but no\ncomment from the White House,\nthat the report may be a prelude to\ngovernment seizure of the mines.\nA White House source said, how\never, i^that there may be further\ncuts in railroad freight and pas\nsenger service beyond those al\nready ordered.\nThe OWMR report painted an\nawesome picture of the grave\nsituation which confronts the na\ntion as result of the strike.\n\"Manufacturing plants are clos\ning down all over the country,\u201d it\nbegan. \u2018\u2018And yet the American peo\nple have barely begun to feel the\nimpact of this national disaster.\n\u2018The basic industries\u2014particu\nlarly steel\u2014have received the ini\ntial body blow from the strike.\nThe impact on even these indus\ntries has been cushioned by stocks\non hand and in transit.\nBut from now on the effects\nwill spread rapidly throughout the\necorf>my and the damage to re\nconversion Urogress will take\nmonths to mend.\u201d\nIt said inventories of coal have\nbeen \u2018\u2018nearly exhausted\u201d and in\nventories of raw materials depend\nent on coal are being depleted.\nEven after the miners return to\nthe Jits, it said, it will take 10\ndays to two weeks before coal con\nsumers begin to receive a regular\nsupply.\nINDUSTRY CRIPPLED\nCHICAGO, May 4 (U.R) \u2014The\ncoal shortage crippled the nation\u2019s\nindustry tonight and plunged three\ncities into semi-darkness.\nThousands of railroad, steel mill\nand farm equipment employes\nwere working part time or not at\nall. Brownouts affected the daily\nlives of six million persons in Chi\ncago, Washington and Philadel\nphia.\nNegotiations on the coal strike\nrecessed and federal med%itors\ntold both sides to \u201cgo to church\nSunday, kneel down and pray to\nGod for guidance to find a solution\nto these problems.\u201d\nThe Illinois commerce com'mis\nsion gave railroads almost blanket\npermission to trim schedules, and\nfive roads operating out of Chi\ncago already have announced cut\nranging up to 40 per cent. The\nOffice of Defense Transportation\nhas ordered nation-wide rail cur\ntailments beginning May 10.\nPullman-Standard Car Manu\nfacturing Co., employing 12,000\npeople, said the company\u2019s plants\nat Chicago, Worcester, Mass.,\nHammond, Ind., Michigan City,\nInd., Butler, Pa., and Besemer,\nAla., already were operating on\nreduced schedules and were threat\nened with shutdowns.\nThe Railway Express Agency\nbanned all except essential ship\nments beginning May 10.\na\nv MOTHERS DAY\nt...\n9\nGive A\nMake this Mother's day a true tribute to your own wonderful \"first lady.\"\nRemember her on May 12th with personal gifts she'll love and cherish. With\nMother in mind, we've collected gifts galore from all parts of the worI5. We\nnow have them all under one roof\u2014our store. We shall be glad to help you\nwith your selections Come in today and find gracious ways to say \"It's\nyour day, Mother!\"\nGIVE A\nSNOW WHITE HANDBAGS\nFashions born yesterday\u2014Just breezed in!\nr Scarf\nLong scarfs in sof! sheer chiffon in all while.\nAlso colorful prints. 30 inch taffeta squares\nin all while or pastel shades. Exquisite com\nbination colors that blend perfectly.\nAs featured in MADEMOISELLE\n1-00\nand\n1.98\nlor Ever Changing Fashion'\nThe Never Changing Beauty of\nYou can give oi\u2019 receive\nno finer pearls*. Illustrated\nis the beautiful Marvella\nZenith, 4.95, 7.50, 10.00,\n14.00 (plus 20% Fed. Tax).\ni\nGreai values in elegant plastic. Washable and easy to clean.\nResists scuffing. Will not crack. Bags with plain or novel\nshell trimings. Under-Arm envelope with top zippers Pouch\nwith drawstring. Top handle of plastic rings.\n4.95 7.95 10.95\nJpKWM\nty LYNETTE\nThe fragrance that beckons gaily to romance;;*\nholds it with a light heart. Perfume, $1.50 to $17*\ntoilet water. $1.2 5 j dusting powder, $1.50. Plus tax;\nMAIN FLOOR\nDANIEL GREENE\n$3.95\nWhites, aqua, wine, Hat heels\nand dress heels.\nftdk-lfrillicutM","height":"27112","width":"20120"}}
